Chapter 4: Site 9
The transport bus hissed as its hydraulic suspension lowered onto the cracked asphalt of Site 9. Outside, the landscape was a graveyard of rusted cranes and half-finished skyscrapers, all swallowed by a thick, yellow fog that tasted like sulfur.
"Everyone out! Check your seals! If I see a single millimeter of exposed skin, you’re on cleanup duty for a month!" Instructor Graves stood at the front of the bus, his hand resting on the hilt of a heavy combat blade.
Ren stepped off the bus, his boots crunching on glass. He adjusted his gear—a standard-issue student vest, far bulkier than the sleek, reinforced armor Kaelen and the higher-ranks wore.
"Look at this place," Jax muttered, stepping off behind Ren. He slammed a fresh Essence-cell into his gauntlet. "It’s a playground. No wonder they send the seniors here to farm Rank points."
"It’s too quiet, Jax," Mira whispered, her sensor-staff humming softly as she swept the area. "The background radiation is low. Too low. It’s like the air is being... scrubbed."
"Maybe the Voids are scared of me," Jax laughed, though he kept his eyes on the fog.
Professor Aris stood near the center of the ruins, holding a holographic map. "Listen up. This is a search-and-contain exercise. You will split into your designated cells. Your goal is to locate 'Echo Traces' and tag them. Do not engage any Void entity higher than Grade 1 without a faculty member present. Is that clear?"
"Crystal," Kaelen said, his eyes already glowing with that faint, predatory light.
As the groups moved out, Ren felt a sharp, pulsing heat in his pocket. The metal disc was vibrating.
"Ren, you’re with us," Mira said, grabbing his sleeve. "Graves put you in our cell for 'Technical Support.'"
"More like a human shield," Jax added, though he stayed close to them.
They moved into the skeleton of a department store. Shattered mannequins lay scattered across the floor, their plastic faces melted into expressions of agony. Ren’s handheld scanner was still dead—except for the single line of text: [Objective: Destination: Site 9].
"Stop," Ren said suddenly.
"What now, Zero?" Jax snapped, turning around.
"The wind. It stopped."
The group went silent. Ren was right. The yellow fog had gone perfectly still. Then, a sound started. Not from the fog, but from the floor beneath them. A wet, rhythmic slapping sound. Plip. Plip. Plip.
"The ceiling," Mira gasped, pointing up.
The black, tar-like sludge Ren had seen in the basement was dripping from the rusted girders above. But it wasn't just dripping; it was gathering. The drops were crawling toward each other, merging into a shape that lacked bones or a face—just a mass of oily limbs and a single, jagged hole where a mouth should be.
"That's not a Grade 1," Mira’s voice cracked. "My staff isn't picking up an Essence signature. It’s... it’s a ghost."
"It’s just a slime!" Jax roared, his gauntlet erupting in a burst of kinetic energy. "Watch this!"
He lunged forward, slamming his fist into the center of the mass. The impact should have shattered concrete. Instead, his hand sank into the sludge.
"What—?"
The creature didn't recoil. It expanded. The black mass surged up Jax’s arm like a liquid vine.
"Get it off! It’s cold! It’s so cold!" Jax screamed, his Rank-C armor cracking under the pressure of the slime's grip.
"Jax!" Mira swung her staff, emitting a high-frequency pulse. It passed right through the creature, hitting the wall behind it.
The creature turned. A second "mouth" opened in its torso, and a sound erupted—not a roar, but the recorded sound of Jax’s own scream from three seconds ago.
Ren watched as the black threads began to spread toward him and Mira. His vision began to blur. The edges of the world started to fray like a digital recording.
[External Interference Detected]
[Analyzing Threat: 'The Hunger of the Void']
[Compatibility Check: 100%]
"Ren, run!" Mira yelled, but Ren couldn't move.
The creature lunged. Its mass expanded into a giant, gaping maw of black oil, aimed directly at Ren's chest.
At the moment of impact, the world froze. The black sludge stopped an inch from Ren’s face. A massive, translucent screen shattered the air in front of him, glowing with a light that didn't come from the world.
[Initialization Complete.]
[Welcome, Architect.]
[System Level: 1]
[Current Skill: None]
[Passive: Absolute Zero — You are invisible to the world’s 'Essence'. You see what is truly there.]
[Emergency Quest: First Harvest]
[Target: Void-Larva (Unranked)]
[Requirement: Subsume the Logic.]
Ren’s hand moved on its own. He didn't punch. He didn't use Essence. He reached out and grabbed the center of the black mass.
"Delete," Ren whispered. He didn't know why he said it. The word just felt right.
The creature didn't explode. It imploded. The black sludge turned into streams of glowing data that poured into Ren’s fingertips.
[Void-Larva Subsumed.]
[Experience Gained.]
[Level Up: 1 -> 2]
[New Skill Acquired: 'Structural Deconstruction']
The world snapped back into motion.
Jax fell to the floor, his arm bruised but free. Mira was staring at Ren, her staff trembling in her hand. The monster was gone. Not a single drop of black oil remained on the floor.
"Ren?" Mira whispered, her voice shaking. "What... what did you just do? Where did it go?"
Ren stood there, his hand still tingling. He looked at his palm. The '0' was gone, replaced by a complex, shifting geometric pattern that pulsed with a dull, silver light.
"I don't know," Ren said, his voice sounding deeper to his own ears.
He looked at Jax, then at Mira. Over their heads, small, floating boxes of text appeared.
[Name: Jax | Rank: C | Status: Fear/Injured]
[Name: Mira | Rank: B- | Status: Confusion/Shock]
And then, he looked deeper into the fog of Site 9. Far in the distance, a massive, towering pillar of black data was rising into the sky—something no one else was reacting to.
[Warning: Major System Error 'The Administrator' detected at the Core.]
